    {
      "id": "48c20b9501b2ee8845a3f7b2cc218bfc950666d7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-15 08:14:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nIn some regards, is prefer if this was done with sizeof(...) instead of just hard-coding the current maximum size, since these structures might change in the future. \n\nHowever, none of the other constants are calculated this way, so the current mechanism is also acceptable.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "74c219ffb39188fc68c54d3d007ae40b56041af0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 141,
        "name": "Li Wei",
        "email": "wei.g.li@intel.com",
        "username": "liwei",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-03-15 08:22:56.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAndreas, I was wondering why the buffer constants were done this way too.  The old comments seem out-of-date and there are magic numbers that I can not figure out how they were calculated.  I wrote some code to print and calculate all mdt_mds_ops operations' buffer sizes, but stupidly \"git reset\" the change away.  AFter that, I lost the interest to completely refresh the constants and comments. :(",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
